      "type": "html",
      "text": "\nThe argument above: \"God directed the writing of the Bible, therefore the Bible is true, therefore God exists and directed the writing of the Bible.\" is a good example of bad logic. It fails on several levels. It begins with the assumption that God directed the writing of the Bible. It assumes that God is real. Therefore there is no need to bring the argument back around. It only works as \"IF\" \"then\" statements. <i>IF God directed the writing of the Bible; THEN the Bible is true.</i>\" the rest doesn't make sense because there is no need for the \"therefore\". The way it is originally written, God is already known to be real, and the \"therefore\" is redundant. -- [[Bruce Pennington]]",
